metadata.title: Cessna 172
aws::graph::propositions: # Cessna 172 Collision Incidents
Cessna 172 is an aircraft model.
N7711G is a Cessna 172 aircraft.
On September 25, 1978, Cessna 172 N7711G collided with Pacific Southwest Airlines Flight 182 over San Diego, California.
Pacific Southwest Airlines Flight 182 was a Boeing 727 aircraft.
The collision between Cessna 172 N7711G and Pacific Southwest Airlines Flight 182 resulted in 144 fatalities.
2 fatalities occurred in the Cessna 172 N7711G.
135 fatalities occurred on Pacific Southwest Airlines Flight 182.
7 fatalities occurred on the ground from the collision between Cessna 172 N7711G and Pacific Southwest Airlines Flight 182.
Reims Cessna F172P is a variant of the Cessna 172 aircraft.
D-ECJB was a Reims Cessna F172P aircraft.
D-ECJB was a rented aircraft.
On May 28, 1987, German teenage pilot Mathias Rust flew Reims Cessna F172P D-ECJB in an unauthorized flight.
Mathias Rust's unauthorized flight in Cessna F172P D-ECJB began at Helsinki-Malmi Airport.
Mathias Rust flew Cessna F172P D-ECJB through Soviet airspace.
Mathias Rust landed Cessna F172P D-ECJB near Red Square in Moscow.
Soviet air defense did not intercept Mathias Rust's Cessna F172P D-ECJB during the unauthorized flight.
N99501 was a Cessna 172 aircraft.
N99501 belonged to Civil Air Patrol.
On April 9, 1990, Civil Air Patrol Cessna 172 N99501 collided head-on with Atlantic Southeast Airlines Flight 2254.
Atlantic Southeast Airlines Flight 2254 was an Embraer EMB 120 Brasilia aircraft.

The collision between Civil Air Patrol Cessna 172 N99501 and Atlantic Southeast Airlines Flight 2254 occurred while Flight 2254 was en route from Gadsden Municipal Airport to Hartsfield–Jackson Atlanta International Airport.

text:
On September 25, 1978, a Cessna 172, N7711G, and Pacific Southwest Airlines Flight 182, a Boeing 727, collided over San Diego, California. There were 144 fatalities, 2 in the Cessna 172, 135 on the PSA Flight 182 and 7 on the ground.
On May 28, 1987, a rented Reims Cessna F172P, registered D-ECJB, was used by German teenage pilot Mathias Rust in an unauthorized flight from Helsinki-Malmi Airport through Soviet airspace to land near the Red Square in Moscow, all without being intercepted by Soviet air defense.
On April 9, 1990, Atlantic Southeast Airlines Flight 2254, an Embraer EMB 120 Brasilia, collided head-on with a Civil Air Patrol Cessna 172, N99501, while en route from Gadsden Municipal Airport to Hartsfield–Jackson Atlanta International Airport.
